text: We are the last family that came from Germany in 1952. We were the last family that they took to America. I remember it because we have pictures and articles of how my grandparents were so lucky to have been brought to America. I think we were the last family. Because of that, we had to come to America much earlier. We had already been told that we would come to America. My grandmother came a year earlier. But then my mother took the child and my brother was born in November just before that. And I think the truth was that it was because of that. And since we were the last family, then later, when there was the Hungarian Revolution and they started bringing these relatives from Hungary, then we were invited to New York. And I remember it so well. I was maybe seven or eight. We were staying in the US. We were wearing American flags and we were greeting them. And it was especially exciting for me because I was so young. For the first time, I was in a hotel somewhere. And you know, we received a very nice response. We did interviews and so on. I think since we were the last family, you know, we became Flying Tiger Airlines. And I know that we flew over to Ireland. And we had to fly to Ireland. Because there was something with the plane. I don't know if it was a propeller or something. Or if it was a problem. But then, again, it was fixed. And I don't think we were there for very long. Maybe more than a night or something. And then we flew back to New York. So we don't have that flight history either. Then we were immediately taken by buses to Seabrook. Seabrook is a small village in Lona, New Jersey. And it's probably about three or four hours by bus. And then we took the bus from New York. And Seabrook because there was a company called Seabrook Farms. Charles F. Seabrook had been building a large farm for more than 30-40 years. And a cold factory there. And it was one of the first deep cold factories in the United States. It was immediately made with deep cold cotton and cotton wool. And he needed a job. And he needed a job especially in the summer months when it was just the harvest season. When all things were growing. Before the Estonians appeared there. The Japanese had come there. And the Japanese, because when America was at war with Japan. Then the Japanese also put them in the slaughterhouses. Because the Japanese who lived in America. Because there was a war in America. They started to slaughter here. Or they started to slaughter more. Maybe, you know, to connect with Japan. To do some kind of big work. Or I don't know what they did. They were Japanese who had lived for years. They had their own homes, their own houses. And it had to be like boarding too. Not only, you know, like boarding in Russia. Every time they put them in the slaughterhouses. They were told to take what you can carry with you. And they were in the slaughterhouses for a few years. And then when the war ended. Then they were given, you know, go now. Live. Search. And of course their homes and places where they had already been. They couldn't go back there anymore. Whether they had been liquidated or sold. Maybe some of them got alone. But basically it was like they had to start a new life. So they also came to Seabrook. Because Seabrook gave them jobs and a life. In the middle of the 1950s there were maybe about 600 people there. 600 Estonians. In my opinion, I have read somewhere that at least 1000 Estonians ever moved through here. Some people came here only for a couple of months and moved on. Maybe they got contact with other people. Or some better jobs. But we lived there. I lived there for 12 years. I think that's why my father had a good place to live. When people came here they were given a place to live. There was furniture inside. There was a toilet. There was a toilet. All sorts of things. They were given a place where they could buy food that they needed. There was a labor service. And my friends were there when I was growing up. Japanese and Estonians. And we were like beggars in school. We were always in the first classes. We had a very strict Estonian life there. It was an Estonian Sunday school that worked on Saturdays. But there was a church component, but also a little bit of Estonian practice. Singing in Estonian. National dance. A little bit of Estonian culture. And Estonian books. Packages in Estonia. It was a big part of my life. To get a package in Estonia. I remember how we gathered for several months. To see what we could get. What Estonia needed. Did anyone want to get some extra money. Then, of course, the money we had grown up with. It was such a good situation. Especially since it was me. And I had three brothers. Two brothers were born in Sibruk. We always had a coffee pack. I don't know where else we went. We had been planning for a long time. How to get it in. And in the end, the packing process. And then some sort of fence around it. So that it was secure. And then the address. And then maybe... I don't know if we had to go to Philadelphia. Or... I think we had to go somewhere far away. Where we could get it. Where we could get it in Europe. Or in Estonia. When I was five or six years old. In 1954 or 1955. I think the first books. I started going back and forth. I remember that. My grandfather. My grandfather Herman Merikani Öde. Who still lived in Tartu. His name had changed a little. He was called Merikandi. Merikandi. Merikandi has been called Merikandi. Merikandi. Merikandi has been called Merikandi. Merikandi. Someone who was a soldier in the German army, or in the police, or whatever. I am in contact with them now. I read these books, I understood them. My mother and my grandmother. What was going on there, what was going on here. It was a test. They reminded me of Estonian times. My grandmother and my grandmother were always reminded of different things. It was like this today. No, it wasn't like this today. What do you know, you were so young, you couldn't remember anything. No, I know very well, I know such things. The thing I grew up with. My mother was such a big fan of communists, Russians, red things. We didn't want to wear red. It was certain. And everything in the world that was red, communists, Russians' food, it was certain. But my mother was, well, she was 16 when she left. And plus, she has this thing, I've heard so much about it, that she had been deported. She was probably killed right away, very quickly. One father died, and the tree where she was buried was broken. The other, those who were deported, there were three children. One was a mother. And that mother died on a train. And at least my mother's story was always that she was thrown out of the train window. She died as a child. When you grow up as a refugee. I remember that, yes. Friends with whom you grow up, who are not Estonians, for example, Americans. They have grandparents, they have grandparents. They have dads, they have aunts. They have some relatives. They have children. You read children's stories. Oh, let's go up to the children. Let's see what old things are there. I didn't have any of those things. We didn't have any old things anywhere. We only had the things that we had when we came. We didn't have any old memories of this country. All our things were in Estonia. Our memories, our children, our old things, our, you know, some relatives. So, this coming to Estonia was a homecoming. A homecoming for a person who has never been there. But it was a homecoming. You come down from the ship. And then you see that there is this, what was it? A wheelbarrow. But wheels. Wheels. And you are here. And you see through it. It was like a wheelbarrow. And I immediately walked there. And everyone was standing there in a row. And I felt them all. I had never seen them in my life. But I had grown up with books. Like my grandmother and grandmother. We used to read them all the time. I stood there. I said, think. There were Livi. Elmo. Kai. Matti. And it was really a pleasure to learn. People with whom you have grown up a little. But you haven't seen them in your life. But they are your own right now. They come from that time. And hopefully, they will. That is how my foundation ended up. I said. That it would not be an extraordinary success. Yes. But you doubt it. And they told me. And I said. Joaquín. You are the only one who is still Namibian. And I said I am the only one. So. But that eventually happened. I realize that a new day has arrived. Yes. And an penguin came to me. But I had met him.
